the landscape history of two centuries to underscore how forest and ecosystem change offered a reliable barometer to the health and stability of the political system that governed them.Cold War Ecology records how East German leaders' indifference to human rights and their disregard for the landscape affected the rural economy, forests, and population. This lesson from history suggests new ways of thinking about the health of ecosystems and landscapes, Nelson shows, and he proposes assessing the stability of modern political systems based on the environment's system qualities rather than on political leaders' goals and beliefs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAgriculture and politicsxHistoryxGermany (East). 0aAgriculture and politicszGermany (East)xHistory. 0aForest policyxHistoryxGermany (East). 0aForest policyzGermany (East)xHistory. 0aForests and forestryxPolitical aspectsxHistoryxGermany (East). 0aForests and forestryxPolitical aspectszGermany (East)xHistory. 0aHuman ecologyxHistoryxGermany (East)xGermany (East). 0aHuman ecologyzGermany (East)xHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300130300423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300130300.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles